            'final_result': '# Segment Adjusted EBITDA: Add-Backs and Why Construction Matters for Cross-Segment Comparison\n\n## The Four Add-Backs\n\nAs defined in the S-1, **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** reconciles from **segment income (loss) from operations** (the most directly comparable GAAP measure) by adding back four categories:\n\n| Add-Back | Nature | Principal Segment Affected |\n|----------|--------|---------------------------|\n| **(i) Depreciation & Amortization** | Non-cash charge for PP&E (satellites, GPU clusters, launch infrastructure) and intangible amortization | All segments, but magnitudes differ radically |\n| **(ii) Share-Based Compensation** | Non-cash equity award expense | All segments |\n| **(iii) Restructuring Charges** | Severance, lease impairment, and settlement costs from X/Twitter workforce reductions initiated in 2022 | AI segment exclusively |\n| **(iv) Impairment** | Write-downs of long-lived and intangible assets (e.g., the $3,775M Twitter→X brand impairment in FY2023) | Concentrated in AI (FY2023) with smaller Space and Connectivity charges |\n\n---\n\n## Quantitative Illustration: How the Add-Backs Transform Segment Economics\n\n### Q1 2026 (most recent quarter, unaudited)\n\n| ($M) | Space | Connectivity | AI |\n|------|-------|-------------|-----|\n| GAAP Op. Income (Loss) | $(662) | $1,188 | $(2,469) |\n| + D&A | 166 | 783 | 1,493 |\n| + SBC | 145 | 116 | 378 |\n| + Restructuring | — | — | (11) |\n| **= Adj. EBITDA** | **$(351)** | **$2,087** | **$(609)** |\n| *Add-backs as % of GAAP loss magnitude* | *47%* | *76% of profit* | *75%* |\n\n### FY2025 (full year)\n\n| ($M) | Space | Connectivity | AI |\n|------|-------|-------------|-----|\n| GAAP Op. Income (Loss) | $(657) | $4,423 | $(6,355) |\n| + D&A | 757 | 2,376 | 3,568 |\n| + SBC | 515 | 369 | 1,063 |\n| + Restructuring | — | — | 487 |\n| + Impairment | 38 | — | — |\n| **= Adj. EBITDA** | **$653** | **$7,168** | **$(1,237)** |\n| *Add-backs as % of GAAP loss magnitude* | *199%* | *62% of profit* | *81%* |\n\n### FY2023 (including the Twitter brand impairment)\n\n| ($M) | Space | Connectivity | AI |\n|------|-------|-------------|-----|\n| GAAP Op. Income (Loss) | $(1) | $469 | $(3,973) |\n| + D&A | 571 | 884 | 1,180 |\n| + SBC | 427 | 249 | 3 |\n| + Restructuring | — | — | 237 |\n| + Impairment | — | — | **3,775** |\n| **= Adj. EBITDA** | **$997** | **$1,602** | **$1,222** |\n\nThe AI segment swings from a $(3,973)M GAAP operating loss to $1,222M of positive Adjusted EBITDA — a **$5,195M swing**, almost entirely driven by the $3,775M brand impairment add-back.\n\n---\n\n## Why Understanding Construction Matters Before Comparing Segment Economics\n\n### 1. D&A Is the Primary Proxy for Capital Intensity — and Capital Intensity Varies Enormously\n\nThe three segments have fundamentally different business models and asset bases:\n\n- **AI**: Massive GPU and data-center investment. Q1 2026 capex was $7,723M (76% of total company capex). D&A of $1,493M in a single quarter reflects the rapid consumption of short-lived GPU assets. Stripping D&A from the AI segment\'s results removes the single largest economic cost of running that business — essentially treating GPU depreciation as irrelevant to economic performance.\n\n- **Connectivity**: Satellite constellation build-out. Q1 2026 capex of $1,332M. D&A of $783M reflects the orbital decay and replacement cycle of the Starlink constellation. Excluding D&A understates the ongoing capital requirement to maintain the network.\n\n- **Space**: R&D-heavy with Starship investment. Q1 2026 capex of $1,052M. D&A of $166M is the smallest add-back, reflecting lower capital intensity in the launch business relative to the asset-heavy Connectivity and AI segments.\n\n**The adjustment is not proportional.** In Q1 2026, D&A add-backs represent 25% of Space\'s GAAP loss magnitude, 66% of Connectivity\'s GAAP profit, and 60% of AI\'s GAAP loss magnitude. Comparing segments on Adjusted EBITDA effectively equalizes their treatment of capital consumption even though their capital intensity differs by an order of magnitude.\n\n### 2. Share-Based Compensation Is a Genuine Economic Cost, Not Merely "Non-Cash"\n\nSBC is a real cost of talent — particularly acute in technology businesses competing for AI and engineering talent. In Q1 2026:\n\n- Space SBC ($145M) exceeded its D&A ($166M), suggesting equity is a primary form of compensation in the launch/spacecraft business.\n- AI SBC ($378M) is a material cost of its rapidly scaling workforce.\n- For Space, SBC alone represents 22% of the GAAP operating loss magnitude. Excluding it meaningfully alters the segment\'s apparent cost structure.\n\nWhile management\'s rationale — that SBC is non-cash and does not reflect ongoing operating performance — is standard, excluding it from a metric used to compare segment economics implicitly treats equity-funded labor as cost-free. This matters more for segments where equity is a larger share of total compensation.\n\n### 3. Restructuring Charges Are Segment-Concentrated and Have Persisted for Years\n\nAll restructuring charges flow through the AI segment and originate from X\'s 2022 workforce reductions. Despite being characterized as non-recurring for Adjusted EBITDA purposes, the program has generated charges in every period presented (FY2023: $237M, FY2024: $213M, FY2025: $487M, Q1 2026: $(11)M credit). The restructuring liability balance was still $312M at March 31, 2026.\n\nThe FY2025 spike to $487M was "primarily due to additional expense recorded to settle with former Twitter employees" — nearly three years after the acquisition closed. Treating these as non-recurring exclusions when they have persisted across four fiscal years and remain unresolved raises a substantive question: at what point does an ongoing multi-year restructuring program become part of the cost of operating the AI segment?\n\n### 4. Impairment Add-Backs Can Reverse Segment Losses Entirely\n\nThe FY2023 AI segment illustrates the most extreme effect. A $3,775M brand impairment (Twitter→X rebranding) was added back, turning a $(3,973)M GAAP operating loss into $1,222M of positive Adjusted EBITDA. While an impairment of this magnitude is genuinely non-recurring, a user comparing FY2023 segment-level Adjusted EBITDA across Space ($997M), Connectivity ($1,602M), and AI ($1,222M) would see three segments with broadly comparable Adjusted EBITDA — but fundamentally incomparable underlying economics. The AI segment burned $6,355M of GAAP operating losses in FY2025 alone.\n\n### 5. The Adjustments Create Different "Distance" Between GAAP and Non-GAAP Across Segments\n\nThe gap between GAAP operating income and Adjusted EBITDA is not uniform:\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 Gap | FY2025 Gap |\n|---------|------------|------------|\n| Space | $311M | $1,310M |\n| Connectivity | $899M | $2,745M |\n| AI | $1,860M | $5,118M |\n\nAI\'s non-GAAP adjustments are 6× larger than Space\'s. A cross-segment comparison using Adjusted EBITDA alone would implicitly weight AI\'s adjustments far more heavily than Space\'s — effectively applying different degrees of "normalization" to different segments.\n\n---\n\n## The Filing\'s Own Cautionary Language\n\nThe S-1 acknowledges these limitations directly: "Other companies in our industry may calculate Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA differently than we do or may not calculate them at all, limiting their usefulness as comparative measures." The filing also warns that the measure "should not be considered in isolation or as a substitute for net income (loss), income (loss) from operations, or any other measure calculated in accordance with GAAP."\n\nFor cross-segment comparison specifically, the critical risk is that **Segment Adjusted EBITDA systematically obscures the most economically salient differences among the three segments**: the AI segment\'s extraordinary capital consumption (D&A), the Connectivity segment\'s satellite-replacement economics (D&A), the Space segment\'s equity-heavy compensation model (SBC), and the AI segment\'s multi-year restructuring drag. An analyst comparing these segments must work backward through the reconciliation rather than starting from Adjusted EBITDA.\n\n---\n\n## Sources\n\n```json\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```'
